'''Hinkley Point C nuclear power station''' ('''HPC''') is a two-unit, 3,200{{nbsp}}[[MWe]] [[EPR (nuclear reactor)|EPR]] [[nuclear power]] station under construction in [[Somerset]], England.<ref name="ITV.com report; 21 October 2013">{{cite news|title=Government closes 'historic' deal to build first nuclear plant in a generation |date=21 October 2013 |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2013-10-21/government-closes-historic-deal-to-build-first-nuclear-plant-in-a-generation-hinkley-point/ |work=ITV News |access-date=31 December 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231034344/http://www.itv.com/news/2013-10-21/government-closes-historic-deal-to-build-first-nuclear-plant-in-a-generation-hinkley-point/ |archive-date=31 December 2013 }}</ref>

Hinkley was one of eight possible sites announced by the British government in 2010,<ref name="newUKsites">{{cite news|title=Nuclear power: Eight sites identified for future plants |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11564152 |work=BBC News |access-date=18 October 2010 |date=18 October 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019043151/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-11564152 |archive-date=19 October 2010}}</ref> and in November 2012 a nuclear site licence was granted.<ref name="bbc261112" />

In July 2016, the EDF board approved the project,<ref name="guardian-20160728"/> and in September 2016 the UK government approved the project with some safeguards for the investment.<ref name="govuk-20160915"/> The project is financed by [[EDF Energy]] and [[China General Nuclear Power Group]] (CGN).<ref name="finance">{{cite news|title=Hinkley Point nuclear agreement reached |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34587650 |work=BBC News |date=21 October 2015 |access-date=21 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021052531/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-34587650 |archive-date=21 October 2015 }}</ref> The final cost was to be £18 billion in 2015 prices.

When construction began in March 2017 completion was expected in 2025. Since then the project has been subject to several delays, including some caused by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-61519609 |title=Hinkley Point C delayed by a year as cost goes up by £3bn |work=BBC News |date=20 May 2022 |access-date=21 May 2022 |archive-date=21 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220521075155/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-61519609 |url-status=live }}</ref> and [[Brexit]], and this has resulted in significant budget overruns. As of 2026, Unit 1 of the station is projected to come online in 2030, while the overall project cost is estimated at £35 billion in 2015 prices (c. £48 billion in 2026 prices), almost double the estimated cost when the project was approved.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |last=Johnson |first=Thomas |date=2026-02-20 |title=Hinkley Point C’s cost climbs to £35bn with confirmation Unit 1 will power up in 2030 |url=https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/hinkley-point-cs-cost-climbs-to-35bn-with-confirmation-unit-1-will-power-up-in-2030-20-02-2026/ |access-date=2026-02-21 |website=New Civil Engineer |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Leake |first=Jonathan |date=2026-02-20 |title=Hinkley Point C nuclear power station costs rise to £48bn |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2026/02/20/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station-costs-rise-to-48bn/ |url-access=subscription |access-date=2026-02-25 |work=The Telegraph}}</ref>

==History==

=== 1980s and 1990s ===
In 1981, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK government]] announced plans to expand its nuclear power stations and the group Alliance against Hinkley C was founded to oppose construction of another plant at Hinkley Point.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Debate |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/western-daily-press-debate/148176282/ |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[Western Daily Press]] |date=19 February 1981 |location=Bristol, England |page=9 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref name="Stop Hinkley">{{cite web |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hinkley Point Nuclear Timeline |url=http://stophinkley.org/hinkley-point-nuclear-timeline/ |website=Stop Hinkley |publisher=Stop Hinkley Organization |access-date=27 May 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220525070508/http://stophinkley.org/hinkley-point-nuclear-timeline/ |archive-date=25 May 2022 |location=Yeabridge, South Petherton |date=2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The following August it was confirmed that the intent was to build Hinkley C.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Stokes |first1=Ray |title=Now It's Hinkley Point No 4 |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/evening-post-stokes-ray-now-its-hinkl/148176163/ |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[Bristol Post|The Evening Post]] |date=4 October 1982 |location=Bristol, Avon |page=3 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> The Alliance against Hinkley C began publishing a newsletter pressing for the government to focus instead on the development of [[renewable energy]] systems and alerting the public to the harm to the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Bruce |first1=Malcolm |title=The Oxford Review |journal=Scram |date=February–March 1984 |volume=40 |pages=14–15 |url=https://www.laka.org/docu/magazines/scram/scram40.pdf |access-date=27 May 2024 |publisher=Scottish Campaign to Resist the Atomic Menace |location=Edinburgh, Scotland |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221220134325/https://www.laka.org/docu/magazines/scram/scram40.pdf |archive-date=20 December 2022 |issn=0140-7341 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Evening Post">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=N-Plant Protests Go on |url=https://www.britishnewspaperarchive.co.uk/viewer/bl/0004769/19900908/002/0002 |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[Bristol Post|The Evening Post]] |date=8 September 1990 |location=Bristol, Avon |page=2 |via=[[The British Newspaper Archive]]}}</ref>

In 1986, the Alliance against Hinkley C was renamed to the Stop Hinkley Expansion Campaign (SHE).<ref name="Stop Hinkley" /> The organisation was funded by [[Greenpeace]],<ref name="Roberts">{{cite journal |last1=Roberts |first1=Jane |title=Clarity, Ambivalence or Confusion? An Assessment of Pressure Group Motives at the Hinkley Point 'C' Public Inquiry |journal=[[Energy & Environment]] |date=March 1991 |volume=2 |issue=1 |pages=45–67 |doi=10.1177/0958305X9100200103 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43734099 |access-date=27 May 2024 |publisher=[[Sage Publishing]] |location=Thousand Oaks, California |jstor=43734099 |bibcode=1991EnEnv...2...45R |issn=0958-305X |oclc=6066755770|url-access=subscription }}</ref>{{rp|54}} and headed by activist [[Danielle Grünberg]] and journalist Crispin Aubrey.<ref name="Shepton Mallet Journal">{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Hinkley Public Inquiry Finishes |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/shepton-mallet-journal-hinkley-public-in/148047890/ |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[Shepton Mallet Journal]] |date=7 December 1989 |location=Shepton Mallet, Somerset |page=5 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Chernobyl Remembered |url=https://www.newspapers.com/article/evening-post-chernobyl-remembered/148047964/ |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[Bristol Post|The Evening Post]] |date=12 April 1991 |location=Bristol, Avon |page=11 |via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref> SHE as one of the major opponents, spent over £50,000 on their campaign to halt construction of Hinkley C.<ref name="Roberts" />{{rp|54}} Members participated in the 14-month long public inquiry, which ran from the end of 1988 through December 1989, and heard from over 600 witnesses. 22,000 people lodged opposition to the construction of Hinkley C.<ref name="Roberts" />{{rp|54}}<ref name="Shepton Mallet Journal" />

Despite the public outcry, [[Queen's Counsel]] Michael Barnes, who conducted the hearings, recommended building the plant in 1990, but said any construction would be delayed until the review of Britain's Nuclear Policy in 1994.<ref name="Evening Post" /><ref name="Shepton Mallet Journal" /> SHE continued to oppose the project and advocated for resources to be spent instead on [[wind power|wind]] and [[wave power]] systems.<ref name="Evening Post" /> In 1995, plans were abandoned to construct Hinkley C or any other new nuclear power plants in Britain.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fagan |first1=Mary |last2=Arthur |first2=Charles |title=Britain's Nuclear Era Comes to an End |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/britain-s-nuclear-era-comes-to-an-end-1525259.html |access-date=27 May 2024 |work=[[The Independent]] |date=12 December 1995 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221005192950/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/britain-s-nuclear-era-comes-to-an-end-1525259.html |archive-date=5 October 2022 |location=London, UK |url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2000s ===
In January 2008 a UK government [[white paper]] announced support for a new generation of nuclear power stations to be built.<ref name="bbc-20080110">{{cite news|title=New nuclear plants get go-ahead |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk_politics/7179579.stm |date=10 January 2008 |work=[[BBC News]] |access-date=10 January 2010 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222000647/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/politics/7179579.stm |archive-date=22 February 2009 }}</ref> Hinkley Point C, in conjunction with [[Sizewell C nuclear power station|Sizewell C]], was supposed to contribute 13% of [[Electricity in Britain|UK electricity]] by the early 2020s.<ref name="new dawn for Uk nuclear power" /> [[Areva]] estimated that their [[EPR (nuclear reactor)|European Pressurised Reactor]] (EPR) reactor design could produce electricity at the competitive price of £24 per MWh.<ref name="ft-20160218">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/9d484f08-d63c-11e5-829b-8564e7528e54 | url-access = subscription |title=Britain's nuclear strategy exposed at Hinkley Point |newspaper=Financial Times |date=18 February 2016 |access-date=19 February 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160220022707/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/9d484f08-d63c-11e5-829b-8564e7528e54.html |archive-date=20 February 2016 }}</ref>

[[Électricité de France|EDF]], which at the time was 85% owned by the French state,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harris |first1=John |title=Hinkley Point nuclear power station: a new type of nationalisation |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/shortcuts/2013/oct/21/hinkley-point-nuclear-power-station |date=21 October 2013 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826184252/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/shortcuts/2013/oct/21/hinkley-point-nuclear-power-station |archive-date=26 August 2016 }}</ref> purchased [[British Energy]] for £12.4{{nbsp}}billion in a deal that was finalised in February 2009, with the nuclear generation business becoming part of [[EDF Energy]]. This deal was part of a [[joint venture]] with UK utility [[Centrica]], who acquired a 20% stake in EDF Energy Nuclear Generation Ltd as well as the option to participate in EDF Energy's UK new nuclear build programme.

In September 2008, EDF, the new owners of [[Hinkley Point B nuclear power station|Hinkley Point B]], announced plans to build a third, twin-unit EPR power station at [[Hinkley Point]],<ref name="new dawn for Uk nuclear power">{{cite news|url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_New_dawn_for_UK_nuclear_power_2409081.html |title=New dawn for UK nuclear power |work=World Nuclear News |date=24 September 2008 |access-date=25 September 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080925133549/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN_New_dawn_for_UK_nuclear_power_2409081.html |archive-date=25 September 2008 }}</ref>
to join [[Hinkley Point A nuclear power station|Hinkley Point A]] ([[Magnox]]), which is now closed and being decommissioned, and the Hinkley Point B ([[Advanced gas-cooled reactor|AGR]]), which has a closure date for accounting purposes of 2023.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/3073749/Nuclear-energy-British-Energy-facts.html | url-access = subscription |title=Nuclear energy: British Energy facts |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |access-date=25 September 2008 |location=London |date=24 September 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080927074509/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/3073749/Nuclear-energy-British-Energy-facts.html |archive-date=27 September 2008 }}</ref>

=== 2010s ===
On 18 October 2010, the British government announced that [[Hinkley Point]]{{nbsp}}– already the site of the disused [[Hinkley Point A nuclear power station|Hinkley Point A]] and the then still operational [[Hinkley Point B nuclear power station|Hinkley Point B]] power stations{{nbsp}}– was one of the eight sites it considered suitable for future nuclear power stations.<ref name="newUKsites" /><ref name=newUKsites2>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/written-ministerial-statement-on-energy-policy-the-rt-hon-chris-huhne-mp-18-october-2010 |title=Written Ministerial Statement on energy policy: The Rt Hon Chris Huhne MP, 18 October 2010 |author=DECC |date=18 October 2010 |access-date=5 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920205321/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/written-ministerial-statement-on-energy-policy-the-rt-hon-chris-huhne-mp-18-october-2010 |archive-date=20 September 2016 }}</ref> [[NNB Generation Company]], a subsidiary of EDF, submitted an application for a Development Consent Order to the [[Infrastructure Planning Commission]] on 31 October 2011.<ref name="planning">{{cite web|title=Hinkley Point C New Nuclear Power Station |work=Infrastructure Planning Commission |url=https://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/projects/south-west/hinkley-point-c-new-nuclear-power-station/ |access-date=14 September 2009 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150810104252/http://infrastructure.planninginspectorate.gov.uk/projects/south-west/hinkley-point-c-new-nuclear-power-station/ |archive-date=10 August 2015 }}</ref>

In February 2013, [[Centrica]] withdrew from the new nuclear construction programme, citing building costs that were higher than it had anticipated and a longer construction timescale caused by modifications added after the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster|Fukushima disaster]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Carrington |first1=Damian |title=Centrica withdraws from new UK nuclear projects |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/feb/04/centrica-withdraw-new-nuclear-projects |access-date=23 May 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 February 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214190028/http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/feb/04/centrica-withdraw-new-nuclear-projects |archive-date=14 December 2013 }}</ref>

The Development Consent Order was published in March 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.somersetwestandtaunton.gov.uk/hinkley-point-c/hinkley-point-c-planning/ |title=Hinkley Point C Planning |access-date=1 December 2022 |archive-date=1 December 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221201110323/https://www.somersetwestandtaunton.gov.uk/hinkley-point-c/hinkley-point-c-planning/ |url-status=dead }}</ref> That same month, a group of MPs and academics, concerned that the 'talks lack the necessary democratic accountability, fiscal and regulatory checks and balances', called for the [[National Audit Office (United Kingdom)|National Audit Office]] to conduct a detailed review of the negotiations between the [[Department of Energy and Climate Change]] and EDF.<ref>{{cite news|title=MPs and academics call for National Audit Office to review nuclear negotiations |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/9975199/UK-nuclear-power-station-given-green-light-Hinkley-Point.html | url-access = subscription |access-date=16 April 2014 |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=6 April 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521072654/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/9975199/UK-nuclear-power-station-given-green-light-Hinkley-Point.html |archive-date=21 May 2014 }}</ref>

In October 2013, the government announced that it had agreed a [[contract for difference]] for the electricity production of Hinkley Point C with a [[Renewable energy in the United Kingdom#Strike prices|strike price]] of £89.50 per [[MWh]], with the plant expected to be completed in 2023 and remain operational for 60 years.<ref name=bbcstrike />

