 |archive-date= 6 March 2016
}}</ref> [[Joaquín Almunia]], the [[EU Competition Commissioner]], referred to the plans as "a complex measure of an unprecedented nature and scale"<ref name="wnn-20131218" /> and said that the European Commission is "not under any legal time pressure to complete the investigation".<ref name="Reuters">{{cite news|author=Foo Yun Chee |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-eu-britain-nuclear-idUKBRE9BH0GF20131218 |title=EU regulators investigate EDF British nuclear project |work=Reuters |date=18 December 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160818183327/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-eu-britain-nuclear-idUKBRE9BH0GF20131218 |archive-date=18 August 2016 }}</ref> In January 2014, an initial critical decision was published, indicating that the UK government's plan may well constitute illegal state aid, requiring a formal state aid investigation examining the subsidies.<ref name="telegraph-20140131"/> [[David Howarth]], a former Liberal Democrat MP, doubted "whether this is a valid contract at all" under EU and English law.<ref name="Howarth" /> Franz Leidenmühler ([[University of Linz]], a specialist in EU [[State aid (European Union)|state aid]] cases and [[European competition law]]), wrote that "a rejection is nearly unavoidable. The Statement of the Commission in its first findings of 18 December 2013, is too clear. I do not think that some conditions could change that clear result."<ref name="Platts" /> Though given that, ten months later the European Commission approved the financing.

In March 2014, the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] allowed [[An Taisce]], the National Trust for Ireland, to challenge the legality of the decision by the [[Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change]] to grant development consent. An Taisce lawyers say there was a failure to undertake "transboundary consultation" as required by the European Commission's [[Environmental Impact Assessment]] Directive. [[Jeremy Sullivan|Lord Justice Sullivan]] said that though "he did not venture that it had a real prospect of success, it was desirable that the court should give a definitive view as to whether there should be a reference to the [[Court of Justice of the European Union]] and, if not, on the meaning of the Directive".<ref name="Western Morning News">{{cite news |title=Judge allows Ireland's National Trust to challenge Hinkley power plant go-ahead |url=http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Judge-allows-Ireland-s-National-Trust-challenge/story-20873547-detail/story.html |work=Western Morning News |access-date=2 April 2014 |date=27 March 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407081625/http://www.westernmorningnews.co.uk/Judge-allows-Ireland-s-National-Trust-challenge/story-20873547-detail/story.html |archive-date=7 April 2014 }}</ref> 
In July 2014, the [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|Court of Appeal]] rejected An Taisce's application on the basis 'that severe nuclear accidents were very unlikely... no matter how low the threshold for a "likely" significant effect on the environment... the likelihood of a nuclear accident was so low that it could be ruled out even applying the stricter Waddenzee approach'<ref name="Francis Taylor Building">{{cite news |title=Hinkley Point C{{nbsp}}— Court of appeal rejects challenge |url=http://www.ftb.eu.com/2014-news/hinkley-point-c---court-of-appeal-rejects-challenge.asp |publisher=ftb |access-date=8 August 2014 |date=1 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019091359/http://www.ftb.eu.com/2014-news/hinkley-point-c---court-of-appeal-rejects-challenge.asp|archive-date=19 October 2014}}</ref>

The [[United Nations|UN]], under the [[Convention on Environmental Impact Assessment in a Transboundary Context]], ordered the [[Department for Communities and Local Government]] to send a delegation to face the committee in December 2014, on the "profound suspicion" that the UK failed to properly consult neighbouring countries.<ref name="The Independent">{{cite news|title=Pressure mounting over £16 billion nuclear site for Hinkley Point |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/pressure-mounting-over-16bn-nuclear-site-for-hinkley-point-9209175.html |work=[[The Independent]] |access-date=2 April 2014 |date=22 March 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407105617/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/pressure-mounting-over-16bn-nuclear-site-for-hinkley-point-9209175.html |archive-date= 7 April 2014 }}</ref>

In September 2014, news leaked that "discussions with the UK authorities have led to an agreement. On this basis, vice-president Almunia will propose to the college of commissioners to take a positive decision in this case. In principle a decision should be taken within this mandate" with a final decision expected in October 2014.<ref name="EC decision">{{cite news |date=22 September 2014 |title=Hinkley nuclear power plant recommended for approval |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-29317800 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922204451/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-29317800 |archive-date=22 September 2014 |access-date=22 September 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref>

In October 2014, the European Commission approved the project, with only four commissioners voting against the decision.<ref name="October decision" /> The European Commission adjusted the "gain-share mechanism" whereby higher profits are shared with UK taxpayers.<ref name="October decision"/>

[[File:Construction of new power station at Hinkley Point (geograph 5569909).jpg|thumb|The site in 2017]]

In June 2015, the Austrian government filed a legal complaint with the European Commission on the subject of the state subsidies.<ref name="The Telegraph">{{cite news|title=Austria to file legal complaint against UK's Hinkley Point nuclear plans |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/11694857/Austria-to-file-legal-complaint-against-UKs-Hinkley-Point-nuclear-plans.html | url-access = subscription |work=The Telegraph |access-date=24 June 2015 |date=23 June 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150624074401/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/11694857/Austria-to-file-legal-complaint-against-UKs-Hinkley-Point-nuclear-plans.html |archive-date=24 June 2015 }}</ref> In September 2020, the court confirmed the aid approved by the commission.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Austria-fails-in-attempt-to-block-Hinkley-Point-C|title=Austria fails in attempt to block Hinkley Point C|date=2020-09-22|work=World Nuclear News|access-date=22 September 2020|archive-date=23 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200923075243/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Austria-fails-in-attempt-to-block-Hinkley-Point-C|url-status=live}}</ref>

In September 2015, EDF admitted that the project would not be completed by 2023, with an announcement on the final investment decision expected in October 2015. Earlier plans to announce Areva and 'other investors' were dropped: "in order to have speed, in the first phase EDF and the Chinese will be the investors".<ref name="The Telegraph2">{{cite news|title=Nuclear delay: EDF admits Hinkley Point won't be ready by 2023 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/11841733/Nuclear-delay-EDF-admits-Hinkley-Point-wont-be-ready-by-2023.html | url-access = subscription |work=The Telegraph |access-date=4 September 2015 |date=3 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909092946/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/11841733/Nuclear-delay-EDF-admits-Hinkley-Point-wont-be-ready-by-2023.html |archive-date= 9 September 2015 }}</ref> A report by the IEA and NEA suggests privatization as one of the causes for British nuclear power being more expensive than nuclear power in other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iea.org/Textbase/npsum/ElecCost2015SUM.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150906025048/http://www.iea.org/Textbase/npsum/ElecCost2015SUM.pdf|url-status=dead|title=Summary|archive-date=6 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rogers |first1=David |title=Report claims UK nuclear costs 'highest in world' as EDF admits Hinkley Point delay |date=4 September 2015 |url=http://www.globalconstructionreview.com/sectors/report-claims-uk-nuclear-costs-hi7g7he7st-world/ |publisher=Global Construction Review |access-date=7 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160821160209/http://www.globalconstructionreview.com/sectors/report-claims-uk-nuclear-costs-hi7g7he7st-world/ |archive-date=21 August 2016 }}</ref>

In February 2016, EDF again delayed a final investment decision on the project, disclosing that the financial agreement with CGN was yet to be confirmed. EDF, which had recently reported a 68% fall in net profit, was still looking at how it would finance its share of the project. With EDF's share price having halved over the preceding year, the cost of the Hinkley Point C project now exceeded the entire [[Market capitalization|market capitalisation]] of EDF. EDF stated that "first concrete", the start of actual construction, was not planned to begin until 2019.<ref name="telegraph-20160216">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/12159337/EDF-admits-Hinkley-funding-not-finalised-as-it-extends-life-of-old-reactors.html  | url-access = subscription |title=EDF admits Hinkley Point funding not finalised as it extends life of old reactors |author=Emily Gosden |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=16 February 2016 |access-date=18 February 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160217093404/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/12159337/EDF-admits-Hinkley-funding-not-finalised-as-it-extends-life-of-old-reactors.html |archive-date=17 February 2016 }}</ref><ref name="bbc-20160127">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-35415187 |title=Decision on new nuclear power plant 'delayed' |work=BBC News |date=27 January 2016 |access-date=18 February 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160205041540/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-35415187 |archive-date= 5 February 2016 }}</ref>

In June 2016, EDF executives and managers told [[Member of Parliament|MPs]] that the Hinkley Point C proposal should be postponed until it had "solved a litany of problems", including EDF's "soaring debts". EDF said it would delay a final investment decision until September 2016.<ref>{{cite news | first1 = Terry | last1 = Macalister | url = https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/17/edf-senior-managers-hinkley-point-postpone-letter-mps-energy-committee  | url-access = subscription | title = Hinkley Point should be postponed | work = The Guardian | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622064947/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/17/edf-senior-managers-hinkley-point-postpone-letter-mps-energy-committee | url-status = live| archive-date = 22 June 2016 | date = 18 June 2016}}</ref>

On 28 July 2016, the EDF board approved the project when 10 out of 17 directors voted yes on the final investment decision.<ref name="guardian-20160728">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jul/28/hinkley-point-c-to-go-ahead-after-edf-board-approves-project |title=Hinkley Point C to go ahead after EDF board approves project |author=Graham Ruddick |newspaper=The Guardian |date=28 July 2016 |access-date=28 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729162618/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jul/28/hinkley-point-c-to-go-ahead-after-edf-board-approves-project |archive-date=29 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hinkley Point C: EDF's Board of Directors approves the final investment decision|url=http://media.edfenergy.com/r/1132/hinkley_point_c__edf_s_board_of_directors_approves_the|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190103170034/http://media.edfenergy.com/r/1132/hinkley_point_c__edf_s_board_of_directors_approves_the|url-status=dead|archive-date=3 January 2019|publisher=EDF Energy|access-date=7 August 2016}}</ref> [[Gérard Magnin]], a director of EDF who was opposed to the project, resigned before the vote.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ruddick |first1=Graham |title=Resignation of EDF director paves way for Hinkley Point go-ahead |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/28/resignation-edf-director-hinkley-point-gerard-magnin |access-date=7 August 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=28 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729165005/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/28/resignation-edf-director-hinkley-point-gerard-magnin |archive-date=29 July 2016 }}</ref> On the same day, the [[Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy]] [[Greg Clark]] announced that the government would delay its decision until the autumn of 2016 to "consider carefully all the component parts of this project", including Britain's [[national security]].<ref name="telegraph-20160728">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/28/green-light-for-hinkley-point-as-new-18bn-nuclear-plant-approved/ | url-access = subscription |title=Government delays Hinkley nuclear decision despite EDF approval for £18 billion project |author=Emily Gosden |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=28 July 2016 |access-date=28 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729172440/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/28/green-light-for-hinkley-point-as-new-18bn-nuclear-plant-approved/ |archive-date=29 July 2016 }}</ref>

On 8 August 2016, [[Liu Xiaoming]], China's ambassador to Britain, wrote that the UK risked major power shortages by 2025, the Hinkley Point C project is ready to go ahead, the 'UK could not have a better partner than the China General Nuclear Power Corporation', and 'the China-UK relationship is at a crucial historical juncture'.<ref name=Xiaoming>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/b8bc62dc-5d74-11e6-bb77-a121aa8abd95 | url-access = subscription |title=Hinkley Point is a test of mutual trust between UK and China |author=Liu Xiaoming |newspaper=Financial Times |date=8 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811190904/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/b8bc62dc-5d74-11e6-bb77-a121aa8abd95.html |archive-date=11 August 2016 }}</ref>

In August 2016, it was reported that 'civil servants are looking to see if there is any loophole, clause or issue in contracts yet to be signed that allow the Government to pull back without huge loss and while also saving face',<ref name=Loophole>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/hinkley-point-edf-nuclear-power-station-deal-how-uk-could-pull-out-a7207776.html |title=Hinkley Point nuclear power station: Whitehall officials 'exploring ways UK could pull out of deal' |author=Joe Watts |newspaper=Independent |date=24 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160827233721/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/hinkley-point-edf-nuclear-power-station-deal-how-uk-could-pull-out-a7207776.html |archive-date=27 August 2016 }}</ref> that Beijing 'will resist any compromise on the deal',<ref name=Refusal>{{cite news|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/china-will-refuse-rewrite-terms-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-plant-deal-1578479 |title=China 'will refuse' to rewrite terms of Hinkley Point C nuclear plant deal |author=Brendan Cole |newspaper=International Business Times |date=29 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830160704/http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/china-will-refuse-rewrite-terms-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-plant-deal-1578479 |archive-date=30 August 2016 }}</ref> and that one option under consideration is to approve Hinkley Point C but delay a decision on the [[Bradwell nuclear power station#Future plans|Bradwell]] reactor.<ref name=Option>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/29/uk-government-could-approve-hinkley-point-delay-essex-project-bradwell-china |title=UK government could approve Hinkley Point but delay Essex project |author=Sean Farrell |newspaper=The Guardian |date=29 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160830075914/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/aug/29/uk-government-could-approve-hinkley-point-delay-essex-project-bradwell-china |archive-date=30 August 2016 }}</ref> In September 2016, the UK government announced after its review "significant new safeguards".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mason |first1=Rowena |last2=Goodley |first2=Simon |title=Hinkley Point C nuclear power station gets government green light |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/sep/15/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station-gets-go-ahead |access-date=15 September 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=15 September 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915162804/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/sep/15/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station-gets-go-ahead |archive-date=15 September 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Hinkley Point: UK approves nuclear plant deal |work=BBC News |date=15 September 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-37369786 |access-date=15 September 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915081633/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-37369786 |archive-date=15 September 2016 }}</ref>

In February 2017, the [[United Nations|UN]], under the [[Convention on Environmental Impact Assessment in a Transboundary Context]], 'said the UK should consider refraining from further works' until it has heard back from other countries on whether it would be helpful for them to be formally notified under a treaty on transboundary environmental impacts.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vaughan |first1=Adam |title=UN asks UK to suspend work on Hinkley Point |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/mar/20/un-asks-uk-suspend-work--hinkley-point-c |access-date=24 March 2017 |work=The Guardian |date=20 March 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323212022/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/mar/20/un-asks-uk-suspend-work--hinkley-point-c |archive-date=23 March 2017 }}</ref>

In July 2017, the estimated construction cost had climbed in two years to £19.6{{nbsp}}billion and was revised to £20.3{{nbsp}}billion accounting for the fifteen months estimated delay cost, with a start date of between 2025 and 2027.<ref name="revised costs2">{{cite news|date=3 July 2017|title=Cost of Hinkley Point nuclear plant climbs another £1.5 billion to over £20 billion, as project is again delayed|newspaper=The Telegraph|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/07/03/hinkley-nuclear-costs-climb-almost-20bn-start-delayed/|url-access=subscription|access-date=3 July 2017|archive-date=17 September 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180917182015/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/07/03/hinkley-nuclear-costs-climb-almost-20bn-start-delayed/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== 2020s ===
In January 2021, the estimated construction cost was revised to £22{{ndash}}23 billion (2015 prices), with expected start date of June 2026.<ref name=bbc-20210127>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-55823575 |title=Hinkley Point C nuclear plant to open later at greater cost |work=BBC News |date=27 January 2021 |access-date=10 January 2022 |archive-date=10 January 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220110130940/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-55823575 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In May 2022, another year of delay and further cost rises were announced, bringing the total to an estimated £25{{ndash}}26{{nbsp}}billion (2015 prices), although "the schedule and cost of electromechanical works and of final testing have not been reviewed".<ref name = 'revised costs May 2022'>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-61519609|title=Hinkley Point C delayed by a year as cost goes up by £3bn|work=BBC News|date=21 May 2022|access-date=21 May 2022|archive-date=21 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220521075155/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-61519609|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |date=2022-12-20 |title=Hinkley Point C Update {{!}} EDF FR |url=https://www.edf.fr/en/the-edf-group/dedicated-sections/journalists/all-press-releases/hinkley-point-c-update-0 |access-date=2024-08-07 |website=www.edf.fr |language=en}}</ref> In July 2022, EDF warned there was a possibility of further delay to September 2028.<ref name=ft-20220722/>

On 13 September 2022, a construction worker was killed on site, in a [[crush injury]] traffic accident.<ref>{{Cite news |date=2022-11-13 |title=Hinkley Point C construction worker killed in 'traffic incident' |language=en-GB |work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-somerset-63616806 |access-date=2022-11-13 |archive-date=13 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221113160237/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-somerset-63616806 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-somerset-63681969 |website= bbc.com |title= Worker killed at Hinkley Point C named as Jason Waring |date= 2022-11-18 |access-date= 2023-08-12 |archive-date= 12 August 2023 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230812150719/https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-somerset-63681969 |url-status= live }}</ref>

In EDF's 2022 annual results published on 17 February 2023, the cost was £31{{ndash}}32 billion in 2023 prices, Unit 1 had a start date of June 2027 and a risk of 15 months further delay.<ref name="feb23cost">{{cite news |title=EDF faces shouldering more of soaring bill for Hinkley Point |url=https://www.ft.com/content/ae5fb399-08ce-4045-bb70-45a6531ac5f2 |url-access=subscription |date=17 February 2023 |work=Financial Times |access-date=18 February 2023 |archive-date=17 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230217232521/https://www.ft.com/content/ae5fb399-08ce-4045-bb70-45a6531ac5f2 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=EDF Says Price Tag of UK Nuclear Power Plant Soars on Inflation |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-02-18/edf-says-price-tag-of-uk-nuclear-power-plant-soars-on-inflation |date=18 February 2023 |work=Bloomberg |access-date=18 February 2023 |archive-date=16 March 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230316091903/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-02-18/edf-says-price-tag-of-uk-nuclear-power-plant-soars-on-inflation |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=EDF 2022 Annual Results |url=https://www.edf.fr/backend/collectivites/backend/groupe/backend/groupe/backend/groupe/backend/collectivites/backend/groupe/backend/groupe/backend/groupe/backend/groupe/backend/groupe/sites/groupe/files/2023-04/annual-results-2022-presentation-2023-02-17-v3-2.pdf |page=25 |publication-date=17 February 2023}}</ref>

In January 2024, EDF presented three scenarios for the works, including when Unit 1 would become operational; with planned installation productivity a 2029 start costing £31 billion (2015 prices, £41.6 billion in 2024 prices), with less favourable installation productivity a 2030 start costing £34 billion (2015 prices, £46.5 billion in 2024 prices) or an unfavourable scenario with 2031 start costing £35 billion (2015 prices, £47.9 billion in 2024 prices).<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |date=2024-01-23 |title=Hinkley Point C Update {{!}} EDF FR |url=https://www.edf.fr/en/the-edf-group/dedicated-sections/journalists/all-press-releases/hinkley-point-c-update-1 |access-date=2024-08-07 |website=www.edf.fr |language=en}}</ref><ref name="edf2024h1p33">{{Cite web |title=EDF 2024 Half Year Results |url=https://www.edf.-07/half-year-results-presentation-2024-07-26.pdf |page=33}}</ref>

In February 2026, as part of EDF's 2025 financial statement, the expected first power date for Hinkley Point C was moved to 2030 from the earlier best-case estimate of 2029 due to issues with electromechanical work, while the project's projected cost rose to £35 billion (in 2015 prices).<ref name=":5" />

===Construction work===
[[File:Construction of new power station at Hinkley Point (geograph 5569899).jpg|thumb|Construction work in 2017]]
Early enabling works started in July 2008, with the construction of a car park for a ground investigation programme.
In 2012, EDF purchased the site of the [[Manor of Sydenham]] near Bridgwater which had previously been used as a factory site by [[British Cellophane]],<ref>{{cite web|title=GES006 - British Cellophane Factory, Bridgwater |url=http://www.guerrillaexploring.com/gesite/public_html/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72:ges006-british-cellophane-factory-bridgwater&catid=4:industry&Itemid=5 |publisher=Guerrillaexploring |access-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918022848/http://www.guerrillaexploring.com/gesite/public_html/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=72%3Ages006-british-cellophane-factory-bridgwater&catid=4%3Aindustry&Itemid=5 |archive-date=18 September 2016 }}</ref> including the Grade II [[listed building|listed]] 16th-century building.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sydenham Manor House |url=https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1297180 |website=National heritage List for England |publisher=Historic England |access-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010043043/https://historicengland.org.uk/listing/the-list/list-entry/1297180 |archive-date=10 October 2016 }}</ref>

In 2014, 400{{nbsp}}staff undertook initial preparation and construction work. This work included access roads and roundabouts for increased construction traffic, park and ride schemes for the site workers, and a new roundabout for the village of [[Cannington, Somerset|Cannington]]. Further plans include the construction of a sea wall and a jetty for ships to deliver sand, aggregate and cement for concrete production.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Macalister |first1=Terry |title=Hinkley Point C: the colossus Whitehall wants but is struggling to believe in |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/20/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-plant-boss-nigel-cann |access-date=21 November 2014 |work=The Guardian |date=21 November 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121052239/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2014/nov/20/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-plant-boss-nigel-cann |archive-date=21 November 2014 }}</ref>

In 2015, the factory site was razed to the ground for construction of temporary accommodation for 1,000 workers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Redman |first1=Leigh |title=Revised submission following EDF Updated Draft Development Consent Order and Proposed Mitigation. |url=http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/wp-content/ipc/uploads/projects/EN010001/2.%20Post-Submission/Representations/Comments/Other%20Comments/FS017%20Further%20Submissions%20on%20updated%20DCO%20by%20Cllr%20Leigh%20Redman%28r%29.pdf |publisher=Infrastructure Planning Inspectorate |access-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305022619/http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/wp-content/ipc/uploads/projects/EN010001/2.%20Post-Submission/Representations/Comments/Other%20Comments/FS017%20Further%20Submissions%20on%20updated%20DCO%20by%20Cllr%20Leigh%20Redman%28r%29.pdf |archive-date=5 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Buckley |first1=Colin |title=Sydenham Manor House, Bridgwater |url=http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-373819-sydenham-manor-house-bridgwater-somerset/comments#.V_ptAOgrKUl |publisher=British Listed Buildings |access-date=9 October 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509034918/http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-373819-sydenham-manor-house-bridgwater-somerset/comments |archive-date= 9 May 2016 }}</ref>

Since 2016, the construction site for Hinkley Point C has had its own bus company, [[Somerset Passenger Solutions]] (SPS), a joint venture between [[FirstGroup]]'s [[The Buses of Somerset]] division and the [[Crosville Motor Services (Weston-super-Mare)|Southern National]] bus company. SPS hold a contract to transport construction workers on a number of routes to, from and around the Hinkley Point C site until 2025, using up to 160 buses at the peak of construction. In September 2016, the BBC reported that if construction were to start now, the plant could become operational by 2025.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-36897180 |title=Hinkley Point: What is it and why is it important? |work=BBC News |first1=John |last1=Moylan |date=15 September 2016 |access-date=10 March 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222101407/http://www.bbc.com/news/business-36897180 |archive-date=22 February 2017 }}</ref>

In March 2017, [[Électricité de France|EDF]], after the [[Office for Nuclear Regulation]] (ONR) gave approval to start building, the building of the first parts of the plant proper began with a network of tunnels to carry cabling and piping. Work was also under way on a jetty to land building materials, a seawall, and accommodation blocks.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cdd0d904-154e-11e7-b0c1-37e417ee6c76 | url-access = subscription |title=Hinkley Point construction gets under way |newspaper=Financial Times |first1=Andrew |last1=Ward |date=31 March 2017 |access-date=7 April 2017 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170407233358/https://www.ft.com/content/cdd0d904-154e-11e7-b0c1-37e417ee6c76 |archive-date= 7 April 2017 }}</ref>

In January 2018, EDF said that they were on track to start generating electricity by 2025 and that they planned to start constructing above-ground structures for the power station by June 2019.

The approximate {{convert|2000|m3|cuft}} concrete pour for the first reactor started on 11 December 2018. It was completed over a 30-hour period, creating the first part of the unit one 4,500{{nbsp}}tonne base, a platform {{convert|3.2|m|ftin}} thick. The reactor building will be built on the (to be completed) platform.<ref>{{cite web
 |url=https://nuclearstreet.com/nuclear_power_industry_news/b/nuclear_power_news/archive/2018/12/13/30_2d00_hour-concrete-pour-completed-at-hinkley-point-c-121301#.XDVnobOZdHY
 |title=30-hour Concrete Pour Completed At Hinkley Point C
 |date=13 December 2018
 |website=nuclearstreet.com
 |publisher=Media X Group Digital
 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213213550/https://nuclearstreet.com/nuclear_power_industry_news/b/nuclear_power_news/archive/2018/12/13/30_2d00_hour-concrete-pour-completed-at-hinkley-point-c-121301
 |archive-date=13 December 2018
|url-status=live
 |access-date=9 January 2019}}</ref> This construction start marks the first new reactor build in the UK after a 30-year break, and the second PWR in the UK, after [[Sizewell nuclear power stations#Sizewell B|Sizewell B]].

Completion of the base for the first reactor, the final {{convert|8954|m3|cuft}} of concrete, was achieved in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news
 |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-28/milestone-for-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station/
 |title=Milestone for Hinkley Point C nuclear power station
 |date=28 June 2019
 |work=ITV News
 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701235958/https://www.itv.com/news/2019-06-28/milestone-for-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-station/
 |archive-date=1 July 2019
|url-status=live
 |access-date=3 July 2019}}</ref>
Completion of the base for the second reactor, {{convert|8991|m3|cuft}} of concrete, was achieved in June 2020.<ref>{{cite web
 |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsbase-completed-for-hinkley-point-c-unit-2-7955862
 |title=Base completed for Hinkley Point C unit 2
 |date=2 June 2020
 |website=Nuclear Engineering International
 |access-date=4 June 2020
 |archive-date=4 June 2020
 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200604104727/https://www.neimagazine.com/news/newsbase-completed-for-hinkley-point-c-unit-2-7955862
 |url-status=live
 }}</ref>

Construction utilises the world's largest crane, the Sarens SGC-250 [[ring crane|double ring crane]], which is responsible for lifting Hinkley Point C's heaviest components. More than 600 heavy fabrications, including the five major parts of each unit's steel containment liner and dome, are positioned by the SGC-250. The crane, named ''Big Carl'', was delivered in modular form, consisting of over 400 deliveries.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shell |title=Delivering the World's Largest Crane |url=https://www.collett.co.uk/sarens-sgc250/ |access-date=8 August 2019 |website=Collett & Sons |date=7 August 2019 |language=en-gb |archive-date=16 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230216115405/https://www.collett.co.uk/sarens-sgc250/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="BBC, Big Carl" >{{Cite web|title=Hinkley Point: World's largest crane begins work in Somerset|date=11 September 2019|publisher=[[BBC News Online]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-49673561|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912160834/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-49673561|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="BBC, Big Carl2" >{{Cite news|title=Big Carl: World's biggest crane starts work at Hinkley Point C|date=11 September 2019|newspaper=[[BBC News Online]]|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-somerset-49679073|access-date=12 September 2019|archive-date=12 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190912140920/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-england-somerset-49679073/big-carl-world-s-biggest-crane-starts-work-at-hinkley-point-c|url-status=live}}</ref>

In February 2023, the first nuclear reactor [[pressure vessel]] was delivered to site via the [[Bristol Channel]] Hinkley-dedicated wharf at [[Combwich]].<ref name = pv23 >{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-64784031 | title = Somerset: Nuclear reactor arrives at Hinkley C power station | date = 27 February 2023 | access-date = 27 February 2023 | publisher = BBC News | archive-date = 27 February 2023 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20230227122123/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-64784031 | url-status = live }}</ref>
The pressure vessel was built in France in 2022 by [[Framatome]].<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/work-finishes-hinkley-point-cs-first-reactor | title = Work finishes on Hinkley Point C's first reactor | date = 8 February 2023 | publisher = EDF Energy | access-date = 27 February 2023 | archive-date = 27 February 2023 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20230227122607/https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/work-finishes-hinkley-point-cs-first-reactor | url-status = live }}</ref>

In May 2024, the first of the 520 tonne [[Steam generator (nuclear power)|steam generators]] was delivered to site in the same manner as the reactor pressure vessel.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 May 2024 |title=New images show Hinkley Point C's heaviest delivery yet as the first steam generator arrives |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/media-centre/new-images-show-hinkley-point-cs-heaviest-delivery-yet-as-steam-generators-arrive}}</ref>

Unit 2 is being constructed 20 to 30% faster than unit one thanks to experience and innovation gained from Unit 1.<ref>{{Cite web |title=EDF |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/media-centre/big-carl-lifts-hinkley-point-cs-second-nuclear-reactor-place}}</ref>

