===Permits and licences===

In November 2012, it was announced that the UK's ONR had awarded a nuclear site licence to [[NNB Generation Company]], a subsidiary created by [[EDF Energy]].<ref name="bbc261112">{{cite news|title=Hinkley Point nuclear station: Licence granted for site |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-20499033 |work=BBC News |access-date=27 November 2012 |date=26 November 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121127171507/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-20499033 |archive-date=27 November 2012 }}</ref> This was the first nuclear site licence awarded for a nuclear power station in the UK since 1987, when one was granted for the construction of Sizewell B in Suffolk.<ref name="bbc261112" />

In March 2013, three environmental permits setting levels for emissions from the proposed power station were granted and planning consent was given, but agreement on electricity pricing was still required before building could start.<ref name="bbc-20130319">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-21774652 |title=What price nuclear power? The final hurdle for Hinkley |author=Dave Harvey |work=BBC News |date=19 March 2013 |access-date=19 March 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322180405/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-21774652 |archive-date=22 March 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-21768339 |title=Environmental permits granted for Hinkley Point station |date=13 March 2013 |work=BBC News |access-date=14 March 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130316021805/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-21768339 |archive-date=16 March 2013 }}</ref>
[[File:Stop New Nuclear Hinkley Point nuclear power blockade 134.jpg|thumb|Blockade to protest Nuclear Power Point in Hinkley]]
Through 2013, the operator was in negotiations with the Department of Energy and Climate Change and other government agencies. A major sticking point was a demand by EDF Energy for a guaranteed price for the electricity to be produced, which was about twice the current UK electricity rates. The project is part of the UK's plans to implement a 50% cut in greenhouse gas emissions by the mid-2020s, which provides for building Hinkley Point C and several other nuclear power plants. By 2013, the operator had invested about £1{{nbsp}}billion in site preparation and other start-up costs. If built, the plant will meet about 7% of the UK's electricity needs.<ref name="NYT031513">{{cite news|title=Britain's Plans for New Nuclear Plant Approach a Decisive Point, 4 Years Late |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/16/business/energy-environment/britains-nuclear-plans-at-a-critical-point.html |access-date=16 March 2013 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=15 March 2013 |author=Stanley Reed |author2=Stephen Castle |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130319005553/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/16/business/energy-environment/britains-nuclear-plans-at-a-critical-point.html |archive-date=19 March 2013 }}</ref>

In 2013, Welsh ministers granted permission for EDF to dispose of construction sediment off Cardiff Bay. EDF have said the work 'is not harmful to humans or the environment' but marine pollution expert Tim Deere-Jones claimed the mud 'could expose people to radioactivity'.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-41347137 |title=Plans to dump Hinkley Point mud off south Wales criticised |work=BBC News |first1=Steffan |last1=Messengert |date=25 September 2017 |access-date=28 September 2017 |archive-date=27 September 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927182119/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales-41347137 |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2021, the Welsh Government's expert panel ''Hinkley Point C Stakeholder Reference Group<ref name=":4" />'' investigated the doses to the public and workers and concluded that 'the individual and collective doses derived were below the [[de minimis]] criteria'.<ref name=":3" />

In October 2013, the government announced that it had approved the agreement of a strike price for the plant's electricity, a major condition for its construction.<ref name=bbcstrike>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24604218 |title=UK nuclear power plant gets go-ahead |date=21 October 2013 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020175317/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24604218 |archive-date=20 October 2013 }}</ref><ref name=telestrike>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/10392510/Hinkley-Point-good-for-Britain-says-Ed-Davey.html | url-access = subscription |title=Hinkley Point nuclear power plant to create 25,000 jobs, says Cameron |date=21 October 2013 |author=Roland Gribben and Denise Roland |work=The Daily Telegraph |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021134838/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/energy/10392510/Hinkley-Point-good-for-Britain-says-Ed-Davey.html |archive-date=21 October 2013 }}</ref>

In September 2016, the government confirmed it would give EDF a [[contract for difference]] for power from the project, imposing significant new safeguards for future foreign investment in critical infrastructure.<ref name="govuk-20160915">{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-confirms-hinkley-point-c-project-following-new-agreement-in-principle-with-edf |title=Government confirms Hinkley Point C project following new agreement in principle with EDF |publisher=GOV.UK |date=15 September 2016 |access-date=15 September 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160916193134/https://www.gov.uk/government/news/government-confirms-hinkley-point-c-project-following-new-agreement-in-principle-with-edf |archive-date=16 September 2016 }}</ref>

On 28 March 2017, the ONR granted its first consent to begin construction of the Hinkley Point C nuclear power plant. The consent covers the placement of the structural concrete for the first nuclear safety-related structure.<ref>Nuclear Engineering International news letter, retrieved 3 April 2017</ref>

On 15 March 2019, the [[Environment Agency]] invited comments on an environmental permit application from NNB Generation Company (HPC) Limited for Hinkley Point C Power Station, with a closing date of 26 July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://consult.environment-agency.gov.uk/psc/ta5-1ud-nnb-generation-company-hpc-limited-2/|title=TA5 1UD, NNB Generation Company (HPC) Limited, EPR/HP3228XT/V004: environmental permit consultation / appeal documentation - Environment Agency - Citizen Space|website=consult.environment-agency.gov.uk|access-date=12 July 2019|archive-date=12 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712200307/https://consult.environment-agency.gov.uk/psc/ta5-1ud-nnb-generation-company-hpc-limited-2/|url-status=live}}</ref>

