[[Areva]], the EPR's designer, estimated in 2006<!-- 2016 FT article states "10 years ago", more specific confirmation of the date needed --> that electricity could be produced at a price of £24 per MWh.<ref name="ft-20160218" />

EDF has negotiated a guaranteed fixed price{{nbsp}}– a [[Renewable energy in the United Kingdom#Strike prices|"strike price"]] – for electricity from Hinkley Point C under a government sanctioned [[Contract for difference]]{{nbsp}}(CfD). The price is £92.50/MWh (in 2012 prices),<ref name="bbcstrike" /><ref name="telestrike" /> which will be adjusted (linked to inflation &ndash; £133/MWh in 2025<ref name=guardian-20251128>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2025/nov/28/uk-energy-bill-payers-edf-hinkley-point-c-sizewell-c |title=UK energy bill payers will hand £2bn a year to EDF for new power stations |last=Davies |first=Rob |newspaper=The Guardian |date=28 November 2025 |access-date=28 November 2025}}</ref>) during the construction period and over the subsequent 35 years tariff period. The base strike price could fall to £89.50/MWh if a new plant at Sizewell is also approved.<ref name="bbcstrike" /><ref name="telestrike" />

In 2022, EDF sought to change the contract to maintain the 35 years tariff period should full operation start after May 2029, which triggers the start of the period regardless of operation status. EDF argued the COVID-19 crisis was a [[force majeure]] event, justifying the change.<ref name=ft-20220722>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/cb715de2-1c95-4a13-8b48-33717b1dcc44 |title=EDF pushes UK government to alter Hinkley Point C penalty clauses |last1=Thomas |first1=Nathalie |newspaper=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |date=22 July 2022 |access-date=23 July 2022 |archive-date=22 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220722181131/https://www.ft.com/content/cb715de2-1c95-4a13-8b48-33717b1dcc44 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2016, the National Audit Office estimated that due to falling energy costs, the additional cost to consumers of 'future top-up payments under the proposed CfD for Hinkley Point C had increased from £6.1{{nbsp}}billion in October 2013, when the [[Renewable energy in the United Kingdom#Strike prices|strike price]] was agreed, to £29.7{{nbsp}}billion'.<ref name="NAO">{{cite web|author=Department of Environment and Climate Change |url=https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Nuclear-power-in-the-UK.pdf |title=Nuclear Power in the UK |publisher=National Audit Office |date=13 July 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160717075657/https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/Nuclear-power-in-the-UK.pdf |archive-date=17 July 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/13/hinkley-point-subsidy-bill-quadruples-as-power-price-forecasts-f/ | url-access = subscription |title=Hinkley Point subsidy bill quadruples as power price forecasts fall |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |first1=Emily |last1=Gosden |date=13 July 2016 |access-date=5 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817170212/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/13/hinkley-point-subsidy-bill-quadruples-as-power-price-forecasts-f/ |archive-date=17 August 2016 }}</ref> In July 2017, this estimate rose to £50{{nbsp}}billion, or 'more than eight times the 2013 estimate'.<ref name="NAO2">{{cite web |title=Hinkley Point's cost to consumers surges to £50 billion |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/07/18/hinkley-points-cost-consumers-surges-50bn/ |url-access=subscription |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 July 2017 |access-date=5 August 2017 |archive-date=5 August 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170805180537/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/07/18/hinkley-points-cost-consumers-surges-50bn/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Criticism ====
Research carried out by [[Imperial College Business School]] argues that no new nuclear power plants would be built in the UK without government intervention.<ref name="EPRG">{{cite web|author=Richard Green and Iain Staffell |url=http://ec.europa.eu/competition/state_aid/studies_reports/green_staffell_en.pdf/ |title=The impact of government interventions on investment in the GB electricity market|publisher=Imperial College Business School|date=25 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150509115232/http://ec.europa.eu/competition/state_aid/studies_reports/green_staffell_en.pdf|archive-date=9 May 2015}}</ref> Some pro-nuclear groups have also said that the "strike price of Hinkley Point C is too high".<ref name="actualstrikeprices3">{{cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201617/cmselect/cmwelaf/129/12905.htm |title=The cost of new nuclear and Wylfa Newydd |publisher=HM Parliament |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825221608/http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201617/cmselect/cmwelaf/129/12905.htm |archive-date=25 August 2016 }}</ref>

In December 2013, [[Jim Ratcliffe]], the chairman and CEO of [[Ineos]] said he had recently agreed to purchase [[nuclear power in France]] at £37.94 (€45) per MWh and warned of the Hinkley Point C project: "Forget it. Nobody in manufacturing is going to go near £95 per MWh".<ref name="BBC">{{cite news|work=BBC News |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-25390456 |title=Ineos boss says Hinkley nuclear power too expensive |date=16 December 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131216144710/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-25390456 |archive-date=16 December 2013 }}</ref> Also in December 2013, the chairman of [[Voimaosakeyhtiö SF]] described the Hinkley Point C strike price as "very high", saying "subsidies will drive prices up, as everyone will try to get as high a price as possible. [[Fennovoima]] ([[Hanhikivi Nuclear Power Plant|Hanhikivi]]) will be built without any subsidies, now or ever".<ref name="Energy Post">{{cite web|first1=Karel |last1=Beckman |url=http://www.energypost.eu/rosatom-signs-contract-build-nuclear-plant-fennovoima-finland/ |title=Rosatom signs contract to build nuclear plant for Fennovoima in Finland |work=Energy Post |date=21 December 2013 |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140226041900/http://www.energypost.eu/rosatom-signs-contract-build-nuclear-plant-fennovoima-finland/ |archive-date=26 February 2014 }}</ref>

A 2014 [[Agora Energiewende]] study claimed that a "reliable power system based on wind, solar and gas backup is 20 percent cheaper than a system of new
nuclear power plants combined with gas" based on comparing nuclear and renewable systems where the natural gas energy share remained the same.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|first = Daniel|last = Fürstenwerth|title=Comparing the cost of low-carbon technologies : what is the cheapest option? : an analysis of new wind, solar, nuclear and CCS based on current support schemes in the UK and Germany |year=2014 |website= [[Agora Energiewende|agora-energiewende.de]] |place=[[Berlin]], Germany |url=https://www.agora-energiewende.de/fileadmin/Projekte/2014/low-carbon-technologies/Agora_Analysis_Decarbonisationtechnologies_web_final.pdf |access-date=2023-08-12 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220120152951/https://static.agora-energiewende.de/fileadmin/Projekte/2014/low-carbon-technologies/Agora_Analysis_Decarbonisationtechnologies_web_final.pdf |archive-date=2022-01-20 |url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2016, Third Generation Environmentalism ([[E3G]]) proposed five ways that the UK could be powered at lower cost to the consumers than by Hinkley Point C:
* improved energy efficiency could reduce consumption by more than the projected capacity of Hinkley Point C, according to a [[McKinsey & Company|McKinsey]] report for the government,
* onshore wind power, which is much cheaper, and offshore wind power, which is also likely to become cheaper than power from Hinkley Point C,
* solar power, which by 2016 has become cheaper than power from Hinkley Point C,
* [[interconnector]]s to Norway, Denmark and France, according to a report for [[National Infrastructure Commission|NIC]] and
* savings in electricity due to improved storage and [[smart grid|flexibility]], according to a NIC report for the government.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/damian-carrington-blog/2016/mar/18/five-ways-to-power-the-uk-that-are-far-better-than-hinkley-point |title=Five ways to power the UK that are far better than Hinkley Point |work=The Guardian |first1=Damian |last1=Carrington |date=18 March 2016 |access-date=20 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826012751/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/damian-carrington-blog/2016/mar/18/five-ways-to-power-the-uk-that-are-far-better-than-hinkley-point |archive-date=26 August 2016 }}</ref>

In August 2016, CEO Henrik Poulsen of Danish [[DONG Energy]] argued that the UK's future energy needs can be covered with accelerated construction of cheaper [[offshore wind farms]] instead of Hinkley Point C. Poulsen stated that wind farms could currently undercut Hinkley Point C's strike price with £85/MWh, while others in the industry believe that by the mid-2020s the electricity price from offshore wind farms would reach £80/MWh.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/04/windfarms-hinckley-point-plant-henrik-paulsen-dong |title=Hinkley Point C is not only new energy option, says windfarm developer |first1=Terry |last1=Macalister |work=The Guardian |date=4 August 2016 |access-date=6 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160806000504/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/aug/04/windfarms-hinckley-point-plant-henrik-paulsen-dong |archive-date= 6 August 2016 }}</ref> On 10 August 2016, [[Ambrose Evans-Pritchard]] of ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' wrote that, with growth in energy storage there is little point in construction of [[baseload power plant]]s such as Hinkley Point C and alleged that "nuclear reactors cannot be switched on and off as need demands"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/08/10/holy-grail-of-energy-policy-in-sight-as-battery-technology-smash/ |url-access = subscription |title=Holy Grail of energy policy in sight as battery technology smashes the old order |first1=Ambrose |last1=Evans-Pritchard |newspaper=The Telegraph |date=10 August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811133703/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/08/10/holy-grail-of-energy-policy-in-sight-as-battery-technology-smash/ |archive-date=11 August 2016 }}</ref> (see also [[Load following power plant#Nuclear power plants]]).

On 26 August 2016, the [[Energy and Climate Intelligence Unit]] released a report on alternatives to Hinkley Point C. It found that a mixture of established approaches including wind farms, cables connecting the UK grid with other countries and gas-fired power stations, together with measures to manage demand, would save the UK around £1{{nbsp}}billion per year while keeping the lights on and meeting climate targets.<ref>{{cite web|author=Energy and Climate Intelligence Unit |url=http://eciu.net/assets/ECIU_Hinkley_What-if.compressed.pdf |title=Hinkley: What If? Can the UK solve its energy trilemma without Hinkley Point C?' |date=August 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020144201/http://eciu.net/assets/ECIU_Hinkley_What-if.compressed.pdf |archive-date=20 October 2016 }}</ref>

On 12 October 2017, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that researchers informed MPs that the UK government was using the expensive Hinkley Point C project to cross-subsidise the UK military's nuclear-related activity by maintaining nuclear skills. The researchers from the [[University of Sussex]] [[Science Policy Research Unit]], [[Andy Stirling|Prof. Andy Stirling]] and Dr. Phil Johnstone, stated that without "civil nuclear power ... UK military nuclear infrastructures would be significantly more expensive".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/oct/12/electricity-consumers-to-fund-nuclear-weapons-through-hinkley-point-c|title=Electricity consumers 'to fund nuclear weapons through Hinkley Point C'|last1=Watt|first1=Holly|date=12 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=13 October 2017|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-date=12 October 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012164816/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/oct/12/electricity-consumers-to-fund-nuclear-weapons-through-hinkley-point-c|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Stirling |first1=Andy |last2=Johnstone |first2=Phil |date=27 September 2017 |title=Some Queries over Neglected Strategic Factors in Public Accounting for UK Nuclear Power: evidence to the House of Commons Public Accounts Committee Inquiry on Hinkley Point C |url=https://committees.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/81294/pdf/ |page=2 |quote="If a UK withdrawal from civil nuclear power on grounds of uncompetitive economics were to leave these shared costs borne entirely on the military side, then UK military nuclear infrastructures would be significantly more expensive. If civil nuclear commitments are being maintained (despite adverse economics) in order to help cover these shared costs, then it is this that amounts to a cross-subsidy."}}</ref>

In 2020, EDF announced that the project had resulted in the creation of 10,300 jobs, £1.67{{nbsp}}billion spent with companies in the region, and £119{{nbsp}}million of community investments.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Realising the socio-economic benefits|url=https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/hinkley-point-c/about/realising-socio-economic-benefits|website=EDF Energy|language=en|access-date=27 May 2020|archive-date=4 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200604175859/https://www.edfenergy.com/energy/nuclear-new-build-projects/hinkley-point-c/about/realising-socio-economic-benefits|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2025, the estimated discounted value of future CfD payments was £49.8 billion.<ref name=lcc-2025>{{cite web |url=https://lcc-web-production-eu-west-2-files20230703161747904200000001.s3.amazonaws.com/documents/LCCC_ARA_24-25_11.pdf |title=Annual Report and Accounts for Low Carbon Contracts Company Ltd 2024/25 |page=29 |publisher=Low Carbon Contracts Company |year=2025 |access-date=26 October 2025}}</ref>

===Return on equity===
One analyst at Liberium Capital described the strike price as 'economically insane' in October 2013: "as far as we can see this makes Hinkley Point the most expensive power station in the world... on a leveraged basis we expect EDF to earn a Return on Equity (ROE) well in excess of 20% and possibly as high as 35%".<ref>{{cite news | work = The Guardian |date = 30 October 2013 | url = https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/30/hinkley-point-nuclear-power-plant-uk-government-edf-underwrite | title = Hinkley Point: nuclear power plant gamble worries economic analysts | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160826222134/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/oct/30/hinkley-point-nuclear-power-plant-uk-government-edf-underwrite | archive-date=26 August 2016}}</ref> "Having considered the known terms of the deal, we are flabbergasted that the UK Government has committed future generations of consumers to the costs that will flow from this deal".<ref name="ITV">{{cite news |author=Laura Kuenssberg |url=http://www.itv.com/news/2013-10-30/ouch-energy-analyst-is-staggered-by-uks-nuclear-deal/ |title=Ouch{{nbsp}}— energy analyst is 'staggered' by UK's nuclear deal' |work=ITV News |date=30 October 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131031075546/http://www.itv.com/news/2013-10-30/ouch-energy-analyst-is-staggered-by-uks-nuclear-deal/ |archive-date=31 October 2013 }}</ref>

According to a March 2014 report by [[Policy Connect]], ROE could be between around 19 and 21%, with "broadly two possible reasons...firstly, the risks faced by EDF could genuinely be greater, therefore commanding a higher rate of return. Alternatively, or in addition, the negotiating process may not have been effective in driving down the expected [[rate of return]] relative to risk. A lack of competition in the negotiating process could have been influential here. The European Commission has questioned the likelihood of the first of these explanations, in light of what is already known about the allocation of risk".
<ref name="Carbon Connect">{{cite web|author=Fabrice Leveque and Andrew Robertson |url=http://www.policyconnect.org.uk/cc/sites/site_cc/files/carbonconnect_powerfromnuclear.pdf |title=Future Electricity Series: Power from Nuclear' |publisher=Policy Connect |date=March 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407071005/http://www.policyconnect.org.uk/cc/sites/site_cc/files/carbonconnect_powerfromnuclear.pdf |archive-date= 7 April 2014 }}</ref>

A European Commission decision on 8 October 2014, adjusted the "gain-share mechanism" whereby higher profits are shared with UK taxpayers. Rather than a 50-50 profit share if the project returned above 15%, the revised "gain share mechanism" will see the UK taxpayer get 60 percent of any profits above a 13.5% return.<ref name="October decision">{{cite web|url=http://ec.europa.eu/competition/state_aid/cases/251157/251157_1615983_2292_4.pdf |title=Commission Decision of 08.10.2014 on the Aid Measure SA.34947 (2013/C) (ex 2013/N) |publisher=European Commission |date=8 October 2014 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105033052/http://ec.europa.eu/competition/state_aid/cases/251157/251157_1615983_2292_4.pdf |archive-date= 5 November 2015 }}</ref>

According to [[Dieter Helm]], professor of Energy Policy at the University of Oxford, "Hinkley Point C would have been roughly half the cost if the government had been borrowing the money to build it at 2%, rather than EDF's cost of capital, which was 9%."<ref>{{cite news |title=Government U-turn on nuclear deal |date=4 June 2018 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-44363366 |work=[[BBC News Online]] |access-date=11 July 2018 |archive-date=20 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180720063158/https://www.bbc.com/news/business-44363366 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=National Audit Office |title=Hinkley point C |date=23 June 2017 |url=https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Hinkley-Point-C.pdf |access-date=11 July 2018 |archive-date=19 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171119060313/https://www.nao.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/Hinkley-Point-C.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

In July 2017, EDF said that "if the £2.2{{nbsp}}billion cost increase came to pass, its rate of return on the project would drop from 9% to 8.2%".<ref name="Cost increase">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/03/hinkley-point-c-is-22bn-over-budget-and-a-year-behind-schedule-edf-admits|title=Hinkley Point C is £2.2 billion over budget and a year behind schedule, EDF admits|date=3 July 2017|access-date=3 July 2017|work=The Guardian|archive-date=8 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170708005144/http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/jul/03/hinkley-point-c-is-22bn-over-budget-and-a-year-behind-schedule-edf-admits|url-status=live}}</ref> In September 2019, ''The Guardian'' reported that the additional cost increase in 2019 would bring EDF Energy's internal rate of return "down to between 7.6% and 7.8%".<ref name=ja>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2019/sep/25/hinkley-point-nuclear-plant-to-run-29m-over-budget|title=Hinkley Point nuclear plant building costs rise by up to £2.9 billion|first=Jillian |last=Ambrose |date=25 September 2019|newspaper=The Guardian|access-date=13 November 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077 }}</ref>

===Financing===
The construction cost was given by EDF as £16{{nbsp}}billion in 2012,<ref>{{cite web|title=Building our industrial future |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/file/1405/download?token=gcM0D47gaHPuYvBZ7XqN0y_fjxKHLOvYuZJg1hoqRJc |publisher=EDF |access-date=8 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151126064942/http://www.edfenergy.com/file/1405/download?token=gcM0D47gaHPuYvBZ7XqN0y_fjxKHLOvYuZJg1hoqRJc |archive-date=26 November 2015 }}</ref> updated to £18{{nbsp}}billion in 2015,<ref name="Construction costs">{{cite news|last1=Farrell |first1=Sean |last2=Macalister |first2=Terry |title=Work to begin on Hinkley Point reactor within weeks after China deal signed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/oct/21/hinkley-point-reactor-costs-rise-by-2bn-as-deal-confirmed |access-date=7 August 2016 |work=The Guardian |date=21 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160722021714/https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2015/oct/21/hinkley-point-reactor-costs-rise-by-2bn-as-deal-confirmed |archive-date=22 July 2016 }}</ref> and to between £19.6{{nbsp}}billion and £20.3{{nbsp}}billion in July 2017.<ref name="revised costs1">{{cite news|date=3 July 2017|title=Hinkley Point: EDF raises cost estimate for nuclear plant|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-40479053|access-date=3 July 2017|archive-date=3 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703084510/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-40479053|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="revised costs2"/> The European Commission has previously estimated £24.5{{nbsp}}billion, including financing costs during construction.<ref name="Construction costs" /> Financing for the project will be provided "by the mainly [French] state-owned [[Électricité de France|EDF]] [and Chinese] state-owned CGN will pay £6{{nbsp}}billion for one third of it". EDF 'might sell another 15% stake in the project'.<ref name="finance"/> In September 2015, [[George Osborne]] announced a further £2{{nbsp}}billion UK government guarantee for financing of the project.<ref name=Guardian92115>{{cite news|author1=Katie Allen and Terry Macalister |title=Nuclear plant project a step closer as Osborne makes £2 billion guarantee |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/sep/21/nuclear-plant-project-osbornes-commits-2bn-guarantee |access-date=21 September 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=21 September 2015 |quote=George Osborne has underlined his determination to get the government’s nuclear energy programme moving by providing a £2 billion government guarantee for the delayed Hinkley Point power plant project. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150927044817/http://www.theguardian.com/business/2015/sep/21/nuclear-plant-project-osbornes-commits-2bn-guarantee |archive-date=27 September 2015 }}</ref> In May 2016, a senior official at [[China National Nuclear Corporation]] (CNNC) said 'the final proposal is for the Chinese to take a 33.5% stake in the project. But this will be a combination of [[China General Nuclear Power Group|CGN]] and [[China National Nuclear Corporation|CNNC]]. We haven't yet decided what percentage we are going to invest'.<ref name=CNNC>{{cite news|author=Ben Wright |title=Second Chinese company poised to invest in Hinkley Point |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/05/07/second-chinese-company-poised-to-invest-in-hinkley-point/ | url-access = subscription |access-date=11 August 2016 |date=7 May 2016 |newspaper=The Telegraph |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160803151720/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/05/07/second-chinese-company-poised-to-invest-in-hinkley-point/ |archive-date= 3 August 2016 }}</ref>

In February 2016, Jean Bernard Lévy, EDF Chief Executive, confirmed a 68% drop in net profits and cut in dividend, saying that a final investment decision on the project would follow 'when all this is fully organised'.<ref name="telegraph-20160216"/> Also in February 2016, another source said 'the question of the funding is far from being resolved, EDF and the French state would need to sell assets under good conditions and in a short period of time, which seems quite complex at the moment considering EDF's share price'.<ref name="ft-20160214">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/34a0fbee-d1a0-11e5-92a1-c5e23ef99c77 | url-access = subscription |title=EDF shortfall adds to nuclear plant delay |author=Michael Stothard, Kiran Stacey |newspaper=Financial Times |date=14 February 2016 |access-date=23 February 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218051748/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/34a0fbee-d1a0-11e5-92a1-c5e23ef99c77.html |archive-date=18 February 2016 }}</ref> In March 2016, Thomas Piquemal, EDF's Chief Financial Officer resigned after 'saying the company should wait another three years before making the final investment decision on the project' where Jean Bernard Lévy disagreed 'saying he wanted it to happen as early as next month'.<ref name="ft-20160307">{{cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/ef9d4de8-e3e9-11e5-ac45-5c039e797d1c | url-access = subscription |title=EDF finance chief quits over decision to push on with Hinkley Point |author=Michael Stothard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=7 March 2016 |access-date=7 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308021827/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/ef9d4de8-e3e9-11e5-ac45-5c039e797d1c.html |archive-date= 8 March 2016 }}</ref><ref name="guardian-20160307">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/mar/07/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-project-in-crisis-as-edf-finance-director-resigns |title=Hinkley Point nuclear project in crisis as EDF finance director resigns |author=Terry Macalister |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 March 2016 |access-date=7 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307110816/http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/mar/07/hinkley-point-c-nuclear-project-in-crisis-as-edf-finance-director-resigns |archive-date= 7 March 2016 }}</ref> In March 2016, Jean Bernard Lévy wrote to EDF staff that he was in talks to 'obtain commitments from the state to help secure our financial position' and would 'not engage in the [Hinkley Point] project before these conditions are met'.<ref name="telegraph-20160311">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/03/11/edf-could-axe-hinkley-point-unless-france-increases-funding/ | url-access = subscription |title=EDF could axe Hinkley Point unless France increases funding |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=11 March 2016 |access-date=12 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312003301/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/03/11/edf-could-axe-hinkley-point-unless-france-increases-funding/ |archive-date=12 March 2016 }}</ref> In March 2016, [[Emmanuel Macron]], the French [[Minister of the Economy, Finances and Industry (France)|Minister of Economy, Industry and Digital Affairs]] said that a final investment decision would not be made until May 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilson |first1=Bill |title=EDF decision on Hinkley Point put back until early May |work=BBC News |date=22 March 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-35873786 |access-date=22 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160322181445/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-35873786 |archive-date=22 March 2016 }}</ref> On 25 April 2016, EDF announced plans to sell €4bn of new shares to 'help it finance the building of the Hinkley Point nuclear plant' with the French government subscribing €3bn of these shares 'as well as taking a scrip dividend option for 2016 and 2017'.<ref name=rights>{{cite web|last1=Gosden |first1=Emily |title=EDF shares tumble on plan to raise cash to help fund Hinkley Point |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/04/25/edf-shares-tumble-on-plan-to-raise-cash-to-help-fund-hinkley-poi/ | url-access = subscription |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=25 April 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160828105631/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/04/25/edf-shares-tumble-on-plan-to-raise-cash-to-help-fund-hinkley-poi/ |archive-date=28 August 2016 }}</ref>

In December 2016, [[The Economist]] reported that the British loan guarantees require the EPR reactor [[EPR (nuclear reactor)#Flamanville 3 .28France.29|Flamanville 3]] to be operational by 2020, that the regulator will rule on the future of the Flamanville reactor mid-2017 and that one possible outcome of this ruling can delay its opening far beyond 2018, thus jeopardizing the British loan guarantees thereby preventing EDF from building the EPRs at Hinkley Point.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/business/21711087-electricit-de-france-has-had-shut-down-18-its-58-nuclear-reactors-frances-nuclear-energy |title=France's nuclear-energy champion is in turmoil |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=3 December 2016 |access-date=4 December 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204103918/http://www.economist.com/news/business/21711087-electricit-de-france-has-had-shut-down-18-its-58-nuclear-reactors-frances-nuclear-energy |archive-date= 4 December 2016 }}</ref>

In 2020, the French financial markets authority, [[Autorité des marchés financiers (France)|Autorité des marchés financiers]] (AMF), levied a €5{{nbsp}}million fine on EDF for misleading investors about the cost of the Hinkley Point C in 2014. EDF had claimed in an October 2014 press release that the UK government agreement was unchanged from 2013, when there had been significant changes to the financing plan, which may have artificially raised EDF's share price. AMF also levied a €50,000 fine on EDF's then CEO.<ref name=guardian-20200731>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2020/jul/31/hinkley-point-c-french-watchdog-fines-edf-5m-for-false-claims-on-cost |title=Hinkley Point C: French watchdog fines EDF €5m for false claims on cost |last1=Ambrose |first1=Jillian |newspaper=The Guardian |date=31 July 2020 |access-date=31 July 2020}}</ref>

In December 2023, recently nationalised EDF was confirmed to be the sole private guarantor of the project as it currently stands, with CGN's exposure limited to figures agreed on in 2016. The £18 billion investment estimate underlying that deal has significantly increased since, likely to exceed a £32.7 billion estimate made in 2023 that used 2015 pricing.<ref name=ft-20231214>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/2bccd67f-a3c6-48d1-baa5-8ef9d54cdf67 |title=EDF told not to expect UK to step in to fund flagship nuclear project |last1=Pickard |first1=Jim |last2=White |first2=Sarah |newspaper=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |date=14 December 2023 |access-date=15 December 2023 |archive-date=14 December 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231214212346/https://www.ft.com/content/2bccd67f-a3c6-48d1-baa5-8ef9d54cdf67 |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2024, EDF announced that it estimated that the final cost would rise to between £31-35 billion in 2015 prices depending on various risk outcomes, or between £41.6{{ndash}}47.9 billion in 2024 prices, and Unit 1 operational between 2029 and 2031. The site managing director said EDF had "found civil construction slower than we hoped and faced inflation, labour and material shortages, on top of [[COVID-19 pandemic|Covid]] and [[Brexit]] disruption".<ref name=bbc-20240124>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-68073279 |title=Hinkley C: UK nuclear plant price tag could rocket by a third |last=Jack |first=Simon |work=BBC News |date=24 January 2024 |access-date=25 January 2024 |archive-date=24 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240124143908/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-68073279 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=wnn-20240123>{{cite news |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-announces-Hinkley-Point-C-delay-and-big-rise-i |title=EDF announces Hinkley Point C delay and rise in project cost |website=World Nuclear News |date=23 January 2024 |access-date=25 January 2024 |archive-date=25 January 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240125080712/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/EDF-announces-Hinkley-Point-C-delay-and-big-rise-i |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="edf2024h1p33" />

As of February 2025, EDF had not found investors to replace additional investment from CGN, and was meeting the additional costs itself. EDF had written down the project by €12.9 billion in its 2023 accounts, and a further €1.1 billion recently for inflation.<ref name=ft-20250221>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c546117d-1fbc-47c8-93a8-dd823311d2ac |title=UK's Hinkley Point C nuclear plant yet to attract new investors, says EDF boss |last1=Johnston |first1=Ian |last2=Millard |first2=Rachel |newspaper=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |date=21 February 2025 |access-date=21 February 2025}}</ref> In June 2025 US asset management group Apollo contributed £4.5 billion in "an investment-grade debt financing package for the project at an interest rate below 7%". In March EDF's British subsidiary had €6.7 billion of debt.<ref name=cnbc>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2025/06/20/apollo-to-supply-4point5-billion-loan-to-uk-nuclear-project.html |title=Apollo to pump £4.5 billion into UK nuclear project in major private loan deal |last1=Srivastava |first1=Spriha |last2=Reid |first2=Jenni |newspaper=CNBC |url-access= |date=20 June 2025 |access-date=5 July 2025}}</ref>

==Specification==
===EPR===
{{see also|EPR (nuclear reactor)}}
EDF is building two of Areva's EPR reactors in the UK, with a design net power output each of 1,600{{nbsp}}MWe (1,630{{nbsp}}MWe gross).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.areva.com/EN/global-offer-1477/two-epr-reactors-at-edf-s-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-plant-the-first-of-a-new-generation-in-the-uk.html |title=Hinkley Point, United Kingdom |publisher=Areva |access-date=7 August 2012 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120622123402/http://www.areva.com/EN/global-offer-1477/two-epr-reactors-at-edf-s-hinkley-point-c-nuclear-power-plant-the-first-of-a-new-generation-in-the-uk.html |archive-date=22 June 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/projects/south-west/hinkley-point-c-new-nuclear-power-station/ |title=Hinkley Point C New Nuclear Power Station |publisher=National Infrastructure Planning |access-date=5 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130217022804/http://infrastructure.planningportal.gov.uk/projects/south-west/hinkley-point-c-new-nuclear-power-station/ |archive-date=17 February 2013 }}</ref> 
Four EPR reactors are currently operating, two at [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|Taishan]] in China, one at [[Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant|Olkiluoto]] in Finland, and one at [[Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant|Flamanville]] in France.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20241221-france-s-most-powerful-nuclear-reactor-finally-comes-on-stream |title=France's most powerful nuclear reactor comes on stream after 12-year delay |date=21 December 2024 }}</ref>
The HPC design has significant changes from the previous units, with 20% more equipment than the Taishan design. The safeguards buildings have been redesigned. The HPC technical director stated in 2019 "In effect HPC is a first-of-a-kind plant in a country that has not built a new plant for three decades."<ref name=wnn-20191107>{{cite news |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Costs-and-financing-key-to-Europes-nuclear-future |title=Costs and financing key to Europe's nuclear future |work=World Nuclear News |date=7 November 2019 |access-date=8 November 2019 |archive-date=8 November 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191108004231/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Costs-and-financing-key-to-Europes-nuclear-future |url-status=live }}</ref>

In December 2007, the [[Union of Concerned Scientists]] referred to the EPR as the only new reactor design under consideration that "...appears to have the potential to be significantly safer and more secure than today's reactors".<ref name="NPIAWW">{{cite web |date=December 2007 |title=Nuclear Power in a Warming World |url=http://www.ucsusa.org/assets/documents/nuclear_power/nuclear-power-in-a-warming-world.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081023095126/http://www.ucsusa.org/assets/documents/nuclear_power/nuclear-power-in-a-warming-world.pdf |archive-date=23 October 2008 |access-date=1 October 2008 |work=Union of Concerned Scientists |page=60}}</ref> "The French and German governments have also required Areva to enable the reactor’s safety systems and spent fuel building to withstand the crash of a military aircraft. And in the event of an accident or sabotage, the EPR’s double-walled containment structure would hold up better than the standard single-walled one."<ref name="NPIAWW" />

EDF and Areva have been facing 'lengthy delays and steep cost overruns'<ref name="Shake-Up">{{cite web|author=David Jolley and Stanley Reed |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/24/business/international/areva-nuclear-results.html | url-access = subscription |title=France Warns of Nuclear Industry Shake-Up After Areva Loss |work=The New York Times |date=23 February 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001132304/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/24/business/international/areva-nuclear-results.html |archive-date= 1 October 2015 }}</ref> on EPR reactors being built at Flamanville Nuclear Power Plant in France and at Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant in Finland.<ref name=jk>{{cite news | first1 = James | last1 = Kanter | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/29/business/energy-environment/29nuke.html?ref=global-home | url-access = subscription | title = In Finland, Nuclear Renaissance Runs Into Trouble | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160415163138/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/05/29/business/energy-environment/29nuke.html?ref=global-home |archive-date=15 April 2016 | work = The New York Times | date = 28 May 2009}}</ref><ref name=greeninc>{{cite news | first1 = James | last1 = Kanter | url = https://archive.nytimes.com/green.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/29/is-the-nuclear-renaissance-fizzling/ | url-access = subscription | title = Is the Nuclear Renaissance Fizzling? | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100116034357/http://greeninc.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/29/is-the-nuclear-renaissance-fizzling/ | archive-date=16 January 2010| work = New York Times Green Blogs| date = 9 May 2009}}</ref><ref name=rb>{{cite news | first1 = Rob | last1 = Broomby | url = https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8138869.stm | title = Nuclear dawn delayed in Finland | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130708132124/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/8138869.stm |archive-date= 8 July 2013 | work= BBC News | url-status = live | date= 8 July 2009}}</ref> In October 2013, [[George Monbiot]], a supporter of nuclear power, said that "the clunky third-generation power station chosen for Hinkley C already looks outdated, beside the promise of [[integral fast reactor]]s and [[liquid fluoride thorium reactor]]s. While other power stations are consuming nuclear waste ([[spent fuel]]), Hinkley will be producing it."<ref name="George Monbiot">{{cite web|last1=Monbiot |first1=George |title=The farce of the Hinkley C nuclear reactor will haunt Britain for decades |work=The Guardian |date=21 October 2013 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/21/farce-hinckley-nuclear-reactor-haunt-britain |access-date=25 October 2013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131025174850/http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/21/farce-hinckley-nuclear-reactor-haunt-britain |archive-date=25 October 2013 }}</ref> In February 2015, France's energy minister said that 'an overhaul of the country's state-controlled nuclear energy industry was imminent'.<ref name="Shake-Up" /> On 13 June 2016, the Fédération Nationale des Cadres Supérieurs<ref name="FNCS">{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/energy-and-climate-change/Correspondence/correspondence-fncs-chair-edf-hinkly-c-130616.pdf |title=Correspondence from the Fédération Nationale des Cadres Supérieurs to the Chair, 13 June 2016 |publisher=HM Parliament |date=13 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826011202/https://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons-committees/energy-and-climate-change/Correspondence/correspondence-fncs-chair-edf-hinkly-c-130616.pdf |archive-date=26 August 2016 }}</ref> unveiled a series of problems with the EPR design, including that the French nuclear safety authority ([[Autorité de sûreté nucléaire|ASN]]) may not give the green light to the EPR being constructed at Flamanville due to various anomalies, there may be "identical flaws" in the Areva EPR being built at Taishan 1 in China, falsification of parts from Areva's Le Creusot plant that potentially put safety checks at risk, and multibillion-euro litigation between Areva and the Finnish energy group [[Teollisuuden Voima|TVO]] over delays to the EPR scheme at Olkiluoto Nuclear Power Plant remains unsettled.<ref name="FNCS2">{{cite news|last1=Macalister |first1=Terry |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/17/edf-senior-managers-hinkley-point-postpone-letter-mps-energy-committee |title=EDF's top managers tell MPs that Hinkley Point should be postponed |work=The Guardian |date=17 June 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160622064947/https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/17/edf-senior-managers-hinkley-point-postpone-letter-mps-energy-committee |archive-date=22 June 2016 }}</ref>

In 2016, EDF Directors Thomas Piquemal<ref name="Proposition C1">{{cite news|title=Finance director's resignation highlights deep concern about nuclear project's risks |url=https://www.ft.com/content/cabdca0a-e47c-11e5-bc31-138df2ae9ee6 | url-access = subscription |work=Financial Times |date=7 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160514094444/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/cabdca0a-e47c-11e5-bc31-138df2ae9ee6.html |archive-date=14 May 2016 }}</ref> and Gérard Magnin<ref name="Proposition C2">{{cite news|title=New Hinkley Point nuclear power station may be further delayed |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/28/resignation-edf-director-hinkley-point-gerard-magnin |work=The Guardian |date=3 September 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160729165005/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/28/resignation-edf-director-hinkley-point-gerard-magnin |archive-date=29 July 2016 }}</ref> separately resigned over their concerns about the risk of the project. However, Chris Bakken, an EDF Project Manager, has said that EDF has full confidence they 'won't repeat the mistakes of the Finnish and French EPRs'.<ref name="Proposition D">{{cite news|title=EDF's nuclear troubles rooted in caution |url=https://www.ft.com/content/a31b76ae-ec2a-11e5-888e-2eadd5fbc4a4 | url-access = subscription |work=Financial Times |date=20 March 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526141019/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/a31b76ae-ec2a-11e5-888e-2eadd5fbc4a4.html |archive-date=26 May 2016 }}</ref>

