==Criticism and organised opposition==
{{See also|Anti-nuclear movement in the United Kingdom|Nuclear power in the United Kingdom#Public opinion and protests}}
A protest group, Stop Hinkley, was formed to campaign for the closure of Hinkley Point B and oppose any expansion at the Hinkley Point site or elsewhere in the [[Bristol Channel]] and [[Severn Estuary]]. The group is reportedly concerned that the new generation of power stations will store nuclear waste on site until a permanent repository is found, claiming that this is an unknown length of time and could potentially take decades.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/local/somerset/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8352000/8352537.stm |title=In depth: Hinkley Point C proposals |date=17 March 2010 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007032031/http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/somerset/hi/people_and_places/newsid_8352000/8352537.stm |archive-date= 7 October 2013 }}</ref> The group issued a press release opposing any plans for a new power station on 24 September 2008, when it was announced that EDF had offered to acquire British Energy. The group has acknowledged that opposition in the local area is by no means unanimous.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stophinkley.org/PressReleases/pr080924.htm |date=24 September 2008 |title=Response to BE takeover by EDF |publisher=Stop Hinkley |access-date=25 September 2008 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720052934/http://www.stophinkley.org/PressReleases/pr080924.htm |archive-date=20 July 2011 }}</ref>

[[File:Stop New Nuclear Hinkley Point nuclear power blockade 021.jpg|thumb|right|A blockade at Hinkley Point in October 2011]]
In October 2011, more than 200 protesters blockaded the site. Members of several [[anti-nuclear]] groups that are part of the Stop New Nuclear alliance barred access to Hinkley Point power station in protest at EDF Energy's plans to renew the site with two new reactors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/oct/03/hinkley-point-protest-nuclear-power |title=Hinkley Point power station blockaded by anti-nuclear protesters |date=3 October 2011 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160611145052/http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2011/oct/03/hinkley-point-protest-nuclear-power |archive-date=11 June 2016 }}</ref>

In February 2012, about seven protesters set up camp in an abandoned farmhouse on the site of the proposed Hinkley Point C nuclear power station. They were reportedly angry that "West Somerset Council has given EDF Energy the go-ahead for preparatory work before planning permission has been granted". The group also claimed that a nature reserve is at risk from the proposals.<ref name=hink2012>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-17002517 |title=Anti-nuclear campaigners set up camp at Hinkley C site |date=12 February 2012 |work=BBC News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120218225812/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-17002517 |archive-date=18 February 2012 }}</ref>

On 10 March 2012, the first anniversary of the [[Fukushima nuclear disaster]], 200 anti-nuclear campaigners formed a symbolic chain around Hinkley Point to voice their opposition to new nuclear power plants, and to call on the coalition government to hold back on its plan for seven other new nuclear plants across the UK. The human chain was planned to continue for 24 hours, with the activists blocking the main Hinkley Point entrance.{{citation needed|date=August 2021}}

On 8 October 2012, the Stop New Nuclear Alliance organised a mass trespass at the site earmarked for Hinkley C. A total of eight people were arrested, mainly for cutting through the wire of the perimeter fence.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-19868126 | title = Hinkley Point: Arrests over trespass | date = 8 October 2012 | work = BBC News | access-date = 19 May 2021 | archive-date = 19 May 2021 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20210519165330/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-somerset-19868126 | url-status = live }}</ref> A march and rally was held in the nearby town of Bridgwater two days earlier.

In Germany, the renewable energy supplier Elektrizitätswerke Schönau (EWS) lodged a formal complaint on 28 November 2014 (after the October 2014 European Commission approval), on the basis that the project "breaches Article 107 [[TFEU]] by approving distortive state aids".<ref name=EWSletter>{{cite web |url=https://www.ews-schoenau.de/fileadmin/content/documents/Mitwissen/Atomkraft/EWS_Complaint_Hinkley_Point.pdf |title=Rechtsanwältin Dr. Cornelia Ziehm |date=28 November 2014 |work=Elektrizitätswerke Schönau|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618163133/https://www.ews-schoenau.de/fileadmin/content/documents/Mitwissen/Atomkraft/EWS_Complaint_Hinkley_Point.pdf|archive-date=18 June 2015}}</ref> EWS also launched an online petition, with about 168,000 supporters by June 2015.<ref name=EWSpetition>{{cite web |url=https://www.ews-schoenau.de/campaign.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150627162857/https://www.ews-schoenau.de/campaign.html|archive-date=27 June 2015|title=No Money for Nuclear Power - Stop Brussels! |work=Elektrizitätswerke Schönau}}</ref>

In 2015, [[Nick Timothy]], [[Special advisers (UK government)|political adviser]] to [[Theresa May]], wrote an article to oppose [[People's Republic of China]]'s involvement in sensitive sectors such as the Hinkley Point C nuclear power project. He criticised [[David Cameron]] and George Osborne of "selling our [[national security]] to China" without rational concerns and "the Government seems intent on ignoring the evidence and presumably the advice of the security and intelligence agencies." He warned that security experts are worried the Chinese could use their role in the programme (designing and constructing [[nuclear reactor]]) to build weaknesses into [[computer systems]] which allow them to shut down Britain's energy production at will and "...no amount of trade and investment should justify allowing a hostile state easy access to the country's critical national infrastructure."<ref name="Timothy-1">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/29/hinkley-point-c-why-has-government-delayed-final-approval | title = Why have ministers delayed final approval for Hinkley Point C? | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160730205353/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/29/hinkley-point-c-why-has-government-delayed-final-approval | archive-date=30 July 2016 | work = [[The Guardian]] | date= 29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="Timothy-0">[http://www.conservativehome.com/thecolumnists/2015/10/nick-timothy-the-government-is-selling-our-national-security-to-china.html Nick Timothy: The Government is selling our national security to China] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731135519/http://www.conservativehome.com/thecolumnists/2015/10/nick-timothy-the-government-is-selling-our-national-security-to-china.html |date=31 July 2016 }}, [[Conservative Home]], 20 October 2015</ref><ref name="Timothy-2">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/30/theresa-may-delayed-hinkley-point-chinese-beijing-vince-cable | title = Theresa May 'raised objections to project as home secretary' | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160731203845/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/30/theresa-may-delayed-hinkley-point-chinese-beijing-vince-cable | archive-date=31 July 2016 | work =[[The Guardian]] | date= 30 July 2016}}</ref>

On 23 June 2017, the National Audit Office published a report on Hinkley Point C. The conclusions were summarised as follows: "The Department has committed electricity consumers and taxpayers to a high cost and risky deal in a changing energy marketplace. Time will tell whether the deal represents value for money, but we cannot say the Department has maximised the chances that it will be."<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nao.org.uk/report/hinkley-point-c/|title=Hinkley Point C - National Audit Office (NAO) Report|website=National Audit Office|date=23 June 2017|access-date=23 June 2017|archive-date=2 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170702192550/https://www.nao.org.uk/report/hinkley-point-c/|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 25 March 2018, ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that: "The UK nuclear regulator has raised concerns with EDF Energy over management failings that it warns could affect safety at the Hinkley Point C power station if left unaddressed"; the original ONR report stated "some arrangements are below standard and ONR is seeking improvements against a number of Regulatory Issues that have been raised under Licence Condition 17 (Management Systems)".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vaughan |first1=Adam |title=Nuclear watchdog raises Hinkley Point C concerns |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/25/nuclear-watchdog-raises-hinkley-point-c-concerns |work=The Guardian |date=25 March 2018 |access-date=5 June 2018 |archive-date=4 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180604031935/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2018/mar/25/nuclear-watchdog-raises-hinkley-point-c-concerns |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Chief Nuclear Inspector's Inspection of NNB GenCo Ltd.'s Supply Chain Management Arrangements for the Hinkley Point C Project |url=https://www.onr.org.uk/documents/2018/cni-inspection-hpc-2017.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210618125743/https://www.onr.org.uk/documents/2018/cni-inspection-hpc-2017.pdf |archive-date=18 June 2021}}</ref>

Concerns have also been raised about one investor, state-owned China General Nuclear Power Group,<ref name="auto">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2019/08/15/questions-raised-chinas-involvement-hinkley-point-us-trade-blacklist/|url-access=subscription|title=Questions raised over China's involvement in Hinkley Point after US trade blacklist|first1=James|last1=Cook|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=15 August 2019|via=www.telegraph.co.uk|access-date=13 April 2020|archive-date=28 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200428033324/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2019/08/15/questions-raised-chinas-involvement-hinkley-point-us-trade-blacklist/|url-status=live}}</ref> which has been blacklisted by the [[United States Department of Commerce]] for attempting to acquire advanced US nuclear technology and material for diversion to military use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2002539/china-general-nuclear-power-accused-espionage-its-adviser-us|title=China General Nuclear Power accused of espionage with its adviser in the US|date=11 August 2016|website=South China Morning Post|access-date=13 April 2020|archive-date=10 July 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200710032349/https://www.scmp.com/business/companies/article/2002539/china-general-nuclear-power-accused-espionage-its-adviser-us|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pillsburylaw.com/en/news-and-insights/china-industry-entity-list.html|title=Four China Nuclear Industry Companies Added to "Entity List"|website=Pillsbury Law|access-date=13 April 2020|archive-date=9 June 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200609075109/https://www.pillsburylaw.com/en/news-and-insights/china-industry-entity-list.html|url-status=live}}</ref> As of July 2021, over 100 Chinese engineers were working on Hinkley Point C, utilising their experience of building the [[Taishan Nuclear Power Plant|first two operating EPR reactors]], about 50 of whom were working on site.<ref name=ft-20210725>{{cite news |url=https://www.ft.com/content/c4a3fe02-8535-45a4-aacf-0c4fbce8409d |title=UK looks to remove China's CGN from nuclear power projects |last1=Pickard |first1=Jim |last2=Thomas |first2=Nathalie |newspaper=Financial Times |url-access=subscription |date=25 July 2021 |access-date=3 February 2022 |archive-date=3 February 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220203104243/https://www.ft.com/content/c4a3fe02-8535-45a4-aacf-0c4fbce8409d |url-status=live }}</ref>

Hinkley Point C was an issue in campaigning for the [[2017 French presidential election]], the first round of which was held in April 2017. [[Marine Le Pen]]'s National Front was "fundamentally against" the project that "would divert resources from state-controlled EDF" while [[Emmanuel Macron]] was in support in the belief that it "could reinvigorate the fortunes of EDF".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/04/10/marine-le-pen-could-pull-plug-hinkley-point-project-elected/ | url-access = subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170411190457/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/04/10/marine-le-pen-could-pull-plug-hinkley-point-project-elected/|url-status=dead|title=Marine Le Pen could pull the plug on Hinkley Point project if elected|first1=Jillian|last1=Ambrose|date=10 April 2017|archive-date=11 April 2017|work = The Daily Telegraph}}</ref>

In 2021 the Welsh Government's expert panel ''Hinkley Point C Stakeholder Reference Group''<ref name=":4">{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.wales/hinkley-point-c-stakeholder-reference-group |website= gov.wales |title= The Hinkley Point C Stakeholder reference group |date= 18 March 2021 |access-date= 2023-08-12 |archive-date= 12 August 2023 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230812134405/https://www.gov.wales/hinkley-point-c-stakeholder-reference-group |url-status= live }}</ref> investigated the potential effect of cooling water pumping on fish populations.<ref>{{Cite news|date=2021-03-17|title=Hinkley Point C nuclear plant 'could suck up 182 million fish a year'|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/hinkley-point-c-power-station-fish-suck-b1818580.html|access-date=2023-08-12|work=The Independent |first=Harry |last=Cockburn |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{cite web |url= https://www.gov.wales/sites/default/files/publications/2021-03/the-implications-of-hinkley-point-c-for-wales-environment-and-its-people_0.pdf |via= [[Wales|gov.wales]] |title= The implications of Hinkley Point C for Wales' environment and its people |work= Hinkley Point C Stakeholder Reference Group |date= 2021-03-16 |access-date= 2023-08-12 |archive-date= 12 August 2023 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20230812131814/https://www.gov.wales/sites/default/files/publications/2021-03/the-implications-of-hinkley-point-c-for-wales-environment-and-its-people_0.pdf |url-status= live }}</ref> The results of the CEFAS study TR456 Ed 2, which stated that their "analyses shows that HPC without an AFD fitted would have no adverse effect on site integrity for any of the designated sites",<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Brian |last2=Walmsley |first2=Sarah |last3=Maxwell |first3=David |date=8 February 2019 |title=Revised Predictions of Impingement Effects at Hinkley Point C – 2018 Edition 2 |url=https://www.edfenergy.com/sites/default/files/5_-_cefas_tr456_report.pdf |page=110}}</ref> were contrasted with Dr Peter Henderson's calculation "that the estimated annual capture rate (impingement) of the system will be 182 million fish, and it is likely that many of these will not survive.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Henderson |first=Peter |title=Estimated Impingement and Entrainment at Hinkley B and C |url=https://wsmsaa.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/Estimated-Impingemant-Hinkley.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240806192050/https://wsmsaa.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/Estimated-Impingemant-Hinkley.pdf |archive-date=6 August 2024}}</ref>{{Better source needed|reason=The citation is a single-page PDF scan with no identifiable publisher and no methodology described.|date=December 2025}}

